# Codex Adversarial Review

Target: branch diff against 46b8e2b5ab6a52a5ab5f6326beb65effdefa8d6a
Verdict: needs-attention

No-ship: the new acceptance harness can skip the write-loss paths on Windows, and the new session rollup can hide completed runs that only surface through lifecycle records.

Findings:
- [high] Write-failure acceptance tests skip on the default Windows filesystem (scripts/test-phase-1b-integration.sh:42-57)
  Section 2 is supposed to prove the fail-loud and fallback behavior for learnings write failures, but both sad-path checks are gated on chmod actually denying writes. On Windows/NTFS via Git Bash the probe explicitly sets CHMOD_DENIES to non-yes, so tests 2b and 2c only print SKIP while the section can still pass. That leaves the original high-cost failure mode, silent loss of learnings/fallback telemetry, untested in the environment this repo is being exercised from.
  Recommendation: Replace the chmod-only failure injection with a cross-platform deterministic failure, for example pre-create $PROJECT_DIR/.iago/learnings/patterns.md as a directory so append fails everywhere, then assert fail-loud and fallback behavior without skipping. Keep chmod as an extra platform-specific case if desired.
- [medium] by_session drops lifecycle records, hiding completed sessions without stage events (scripts/metrics-aggregate.mjs:234-249)
  The by_session code only creates buckets for stage_start, stage_end, and the four new event kinds. It ignores pipeline_init and pipeline_finalize even though the file doc lists them as record types for the projection and complete runs are defined by pipeline_finalize. A completed run that fails before emitting a stage, or whose only useful failure signal is pipeline_finalize.pipeline_exit, will show no session row at all, making the new operational rollup falsely look empty.
  Recommendation: Handle pipeline_init and pipeline_finalize in the session projection: create the session bucket for those records, add init/finalize counts, and include failed finalize/pipeline_exit counts so completed failed sessions cannot disappear from by_session.

Next steps:
- Block shipping until Section 2 exercises write failures on Windows-compatible fixtures.
- Extend by_session to account for lifecycle records and add a regression fixture with a completed run containing pipeline_finalize but no stage_end.
